<p><div class="msgquote"><div class="msgquotesrc">Quote:</div><div class="msgqorig">Mobs keep their stats in any expansion or zone created before Gates of Discord. Even GoD mobs keep most of their stats, altho they often lose something while charmed, like the ability to flurry. Mobs in Omens of War or later expansions or zones created after OoW get greatly reduced stats when charmed (usually losing abilities like flurry or rampage, and hitting for much less... it's a sad thing to charm a mob that hits for 1k, only to have it hit for 200 while charmed), but jump right back to their normal stats when charm breaks, making charm in later expansions a big hassle and just not worth the effort except in rare encounters where charm is part of the solution (certain raid encounters), since the first thing they'll want to do on charm break is eat you alive. </div></div> <br /> <br />Just to elaborate on this a little bit, I'm 99% the 'nerfed' charm mobs ONLY lose some offensive capabilities.  HP/defense stay the same.  I've used some of these crummy pets when a tank goes down as a temporary tank until we can get the real tank bank.  Very useful in some situations to throw something with a bunch of HPs in front of you to keep everyone alive a little while longer, DoDH spell mission 68.3 comes to mind specifically where this helped me. <br /> <br />Also, re: spell casting charmed pets.  It's usually a good idea to charm something that is pure melee if you can.  Occassionally I've charmed a caster that had some limited use (healing or shamans with better slow than me hehe), but as was said, they aren't the smartest when casting.  IF you do find one that is useful to you, though, you can mind buffs on it, which seems to help it keep it's mana.  To keep a caster, like an SK, from casting so much, I usually mez it first then drain all it's mana, then charm it.  I also don't let it sit, but that may or may not do anything.  I'm not sure how mob mana regen works when charmed. <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Mon Apr  3 20:01:58 2006 by Semiopaque</span></i></p>
